[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] A BST can be traversed through three basic algorithms: inorder, preorder, and postorder tree walks.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] Following is a recursive implementation of the tree walks.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] Without rebalancing, insertions or deletions in a binary search tree may lead to degeneration, resulting in a height n of the tree (where n is number of items in a tree), so that the lookup performance is deteriorated to that of a linear search.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] Keeping the search tree balanced and height bounded by $O(\log n)$ is a key to the usefulness of the binary search tree.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] This can be achieved by "self-balancing" mechanisms during the updation operations to the tree designed to maintain the tree height to the binary logarithmic complexity.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] A tree is height-balanced if the heights of the left sub-tree and right sub-tree are guaranteed to be related by a constant factor.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] This property was introduced by the AVL tree and continued by the red–black tree.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] The heights of all the nodes on the path from the root to the modified leaf node have to be observed and possibly corrected on every insert and delete operation to the tree.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] In a weight-balanced tree, the criterion of a balanced tree is the number of leaves of the subtrees.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] The weights of the left and right subtrees differ at most by 1 .
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] However, the difference is bound by a ratio $\alpha$ of the weights, since a strong balance condition of 1 cannot be maintained with $O(\log n)$ rebalancing work during insert and delete operations.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] The $\alpha$ -weight-balanced trees gives an entire family of balance conditions, where each left and right subtrees have each at least a fraction of $\alpha$ of the total weight of the subtree.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] There are several self-balanced binary search trees, including T-tree, treap, red-black tree, B-tree, 2–3 tree, and Splay tree.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort, where all the elements are inserted at once and the tree is traversed at an in-order fashion.
[src:skip-list/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in implementing priority queues, using the node's key as priorities.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In computer science, a **linked list** is a linear collection of data elements whose order is not given by their physical placement in memory.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Instead, each element points to the next.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] It is a data structure consisting of a collection of nodes which together represent a sequence.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In its most basic form, each node contains data, and a reference (in other words, a *link*) to the next node in the sequence.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This structure allows for efficient insertion or removal of elements from any position in the sequence during iteration.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] More complex variants add additional links, allowing more efficient insertion or removal of nodes at arbitrary positions.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A drawback of linked lists is that data access time is linear with respect to the number of nodes in the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Because nodes are serially linked, accessing any node requires that the prior node be accessed beforehand (which introduces difficulties in pipelining).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Faster access, such as random access, is not feasible.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Arrays have better cache locality compared to linked lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Linked lists are among the simplest and most common data structures.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] They can be used to implement several other common abstract data types, including lists, stacks, queues, associative arrays, and S-expressions, though it is not uncommon to implement those data structures directly without using a linked list as the basis.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In an array, the data is stored in memory is in contiguous fashion i.e. the data is stored to very next idle memory location to previous one.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] But in Linked list data is not stored in contiguous memory locations, instead the node holding the reference to other node's memory address is in sequential order.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Linked lists allow insertion and removal of nodes at any point in the list, and allow doing so with a constant number of operations by keeping the link previous to the link being added or removed in memory during list traversal.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This practice resurfaced during the early years of mechanical printing of books in Europe, when it was common practice for printers to include at the end of each printed page a "catchword" corresponding to the first word on the page next in order.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The first implementation of linked listing in the computer-science context was developed in 1955–1956 by Allen Newell, Cliff Shaw, and Herbert A.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Simon at RAND Corporation and Carnegie Mellon University as the primary data structure for their Information Processing Language (IPL).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] IPL was used by the authors to develop several early artificial intelligence programs, including the Logic Theory Machine, the General Problem Solver, and a computer chess program.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The now-classic diagram consisting of blocks representing list nodes with arrows pointing to successive list nodes appears in "Programming the Logic Theory Machine" by Newell and Shaw in Proc.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Newell and Simon were recognized with the ACM Turing Award in 1975 for having "made basic contributions to artificial intelligence, the psychology of human cognition, and list processing".
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The problem of machine translation for natural language processing led Victor Yngve at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) to use linked lists as data structures in his COMIT programming language for computer research in the field of linguistics.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A report on this language entitled "A programming language for mechanical translation" appeared in Mechanical Translation in 1958.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Another early appearance of linked lists was by Hans Peter Luhn who wrote an internal IBM memorandum in January 1953 that suggested the use of linked lists in chained hash tables.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] LISP, standing for list processor, was created by John McCarthy in 1958 while he was at MIT and in 1960 he published its design in a paper in the Communications of the ACM, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:skip-list/linked-list] One of LISP's major data structures is the linked list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] By the early 1960s, the utility of both linked lists and languages which use these structures as their primary data representation was well established.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Bert Green of the MIT Lincoln Laboratory published a review article entitled "Computer languages for symbol manipulation" in IRE Transactions on Human Factors in Electronics in March 1961 which summarized the advantages of the linked list approach.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A later review article, "A Comparison of list-processing computer languages" by Bobrow and Raphael, appeared in Communications of the ACM in April 1964.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Several operating systems developed by Technical Systems Consultants (originally of West Lafayette Indiana, and later of Chapel Hill, North Carolina) used singly linked lists as file structures.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A directory entry pointed to the first sector of a file, and succeeding portions of the file were located by traversing pointers.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Systems using this technique included Flex (for the Motorola 6800 CPU), mini-Flex (same CPU), and Flex9 (for the Motorola 6809 CPU).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A variant developed by TSC for and marketed by Smoke Signal Broadcasting in California, used doubly linked lists in the same manner.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The TSS/360 operating system, developed by IBM for the System 360/370 machines, used a double linked list for their file system catalog.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The directory structure was similar to Unix, where a directory could contain files and other directories and extend to any depth.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Each record of a linked list is often called an 'element' or 'node'.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The field of each node that contains the address of the next node is usually called the 'next link' or 'next pointer'.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The remaining fields are known as the 'data', 'information', 'value', 'cargo', or 'payload' fields.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The 'tail' of a list may refer either to the rest of the list after the head, or to the last node in the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In Lisp and some derived languages, the next node may be called the 'cdr' (pronounced /'kʊd.əɹ/) of the list, while the payload of the head node may be called the 'car'.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Singly linked lists contain nodes which have a 'value' field as well as 'next' field, which points to the next node in line of nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Operations that can be performed on singly linked lists include insertion, deletion and traversal.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In a 'doubly linked list', each node contains, besides the link to the next node, a second link field pointing to the 'previous' node in the sequence.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The two links may be called 'forward('s') and 'backwards', or 'next' and 'prev'('previous').
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A technique known as XOR-linking allows a doubly linked list to be implemented using a single link field in each node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] However, this technique requires the ability to do bit operations on addresses, and therefore may not be available in some high-level languages.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Many modern operating systems use doubly linked lists to maintain references to active processes, threads, and other dynamic objects.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A common strategy for rootkits to evade detection is to unlink themselves from these lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In a 'multiply linked list', each node contains two or more link fields, each field being used to connect the same set of data arranged in a different order (e.g., by name, by department, by date of birth, etc.).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] While a doubly linked list can be seen as a special case of multiply linked list, the fact that the two and more orders are opposite to each other leads to simpler and more efficient algorithms, so they are usually treated as a separate case.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In the last node of a linked list, the link field often contains a null reference, a special value used to indicate the lack of further nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A less common convention is to make it point to the first node of the list; in that case, the list is said to be 'circular' or 'circularly linked'; otherwise, it is said to be 'open' or 'linear'.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] It is a list where the last node pointer points to the first node (i.e., the "link to next node" pointer of the last node has the memory address of the first node).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In the case of a circular doubly linked list, the first node also points to the last node of the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In some implementations an extra 'sentinel' or 'dummy' node may be added before the first data record or after the last one.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This convention simplifies and accelerates some list-handling algorithms, by ensuring that all links can be safely dereferenced and that every list (even one that contains no data elements) always has a "first" and "last" node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] An empty list is a list that contains no data records.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This is usually the same as saying that it has zero nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If sentinel nodes are being used, the list is usually said to be empty when it has only sentinel nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The link fields need not be physically part of the nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If the data records are stored in an array and referenced by their indices, the link field may be stored in a separate array with the same indices as the data records.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Since a reference to the first node gives access to the whole list, that reference is often called the 'address', 'pointer', or 'handle' of the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Algorithms that manipulate linked lists usually get such handles to the input lists and return the handles to the resulting lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In fact, in the context of such algorithms, the word "list" often means "list handle".
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In some situations, however, it may be convenient to refer to a list by a handle that consists of two links, pointing to its first and last nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The alternatives listed above may be arbitrarily combined in almost every way, so one may have circular doubly linked lists without sentinels, circular singly linked lists with sentinels, etc.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] As with most choices in computer programming and design, no method is well suited to all circumstances.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A linked list data structure might work well in one case, but cause problems in another.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This is a list of some of the common tradeoffs involving linked list structures.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A *dynamic array* is a data structure that allocates all elements contiguously in memory, and keeps a count of the current number of elements.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If the space reserved for the dynamic array is exceeded, it is reallocated and (possibly) copied, which is an expensive operation.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Linked lists have several advantages over dynamic arrays.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] While one can "delete" an element from an array in constant time by somehow marking its slot as "vacant", this causes fragmentation that impedes the performance of iteration.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This helps with appending elements at the array's end, but inserting into (or removing from) middle positions still carries prohibitive costs due to data moving to maintain contiguity.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] An array from which many elements are removed may also have to be resized in order to avoid wasting too much space.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] On the other hand, dynamic arrays (as well as fixed-size array data structures) allow constant-time random access, while linked lists allow only sequential access to elements.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Singly linked lists, in fact, can be easily traversed in only one direction.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This makes linked lists unsuitable for applications where it's useful to look up an element by its index quickly, such as heapsort.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Sequential access on arrays and dynamic arrays is also faster than on linked lists on many machines, because they have optimal locality of reference and thus make good use of data caching.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Another disadvantage of linked lists is the extra storage needed for references, which often makes them impractical for lists of small data items such as characters or Boolean values, because the storage overhead for the links may exceed by a factor of two or more the size of the data.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In contrast, a dynamic array requires only the space for the data itself (and a very small amount of control data).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] It can also be slow, and with a naïve allocator, wasteful, to allocate memory separately for each new element, a problem generally solved using memory pools.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Some hybrid solutions try to combine the advantages of the two representations.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Unrolled linked lists store several elements in each list node, increasing cache performance while decreasing memory overhead for references.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] CDR coding does both these as well, by replacing references with the actual data referenced, which extends off the end of the referencing record.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A good example that highlights the pros and cons of using dynamic arrays vs. linked lists is by implementing a program that resolves the Josephus problem.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The Josephus problem is an election method that works by having a group of people stand in a circle.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Starting at a predetermined person, one may count around the circle *n* times.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Once the *n*th person is reached, one should remove them from the circle and have the members close the circle.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The process is repeated until only one person is left.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This shows the strengths and weaknesses of a linked list vs. a dynamic array, because if the people are viewed as connected nodes in a circular linked list, then it shows how easily the linked list is able to delete nodes (as it only has to rearrange the links to the different nodes).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] However, the linked list will be poor at finding the next person to remove and will need to search through the list until it finds that person.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A dynamic array, on the other hand, will be poor at deleting nodes (or elements) as it cannot remove one node without individually shifting all the elements up the list by one.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] However, it is exceptionally easy to find the *n*th person in the circle by directly referencing them by their position in the array.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The list ranking problem concerns the efficient conversion of a linked list representation into an array.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Although trivial for a conventional computer, solving this problem by a parallel algorithm is complicated and has been the subject of much research.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A balanced tree has similar memory access patterns and space overhead to a linked list while permitting much more efficient indexing, taking O(log n) time instead of O(n) for a random access.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] However, insertion and deletion operations are more expensive due to the overhead of tree manipulations to maintain balance.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Schemes exist for trees to automatically maintain themselves in a balanced state: AVL trees or red–black trees.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] While doubly linked and circular lists have advantages over singly linked linear lists, linear lists offer some advantages that make them preferable in some situations.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A singly linked linear list is a recursive data structure, because it contains a pointer to a *smaller* object of the same type.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] For that reason, many operations on singly linked linear lists (such as merging two lists, or enumerating the elements in reverse order) often have very simple recursive algorithms, much simpler than any solution using iterative commands.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] While those recursive solutions can be adapted for doubly linked and circularly linked lists, the procedures generally need extra arguments and more complicated base cases.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Linear singly linked lists also allow tail-sharing, the use of a common final portion of sub-list as the terminal portion of two different lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In particular, if a new node is added at the beginning of a list, the former list remains available as the tail of the new one—a simple example of a persistent data structure.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Again, this is not true with the other variants: a node may never belong to two different circular or doubly linked lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In particular, end-sentinel nodes can be shared among singly linked non-circular lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The same end-sentinel node may be used for *every* such list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In Lisp, for example, every proper list ends with a link to a special node, denoted by `nil` or `()`.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The advantages of the fancy variants are often limited to the complexity of the algorithms, not in their efficiency.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A circular list, in particular, can usually be emulated by a linear list together with two variables that point to the first and last nodes, at no extra cost.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Double-linked lists require more space per node (unless one uses XOR-linking), and their elementary operations are more expensive; but they are often easier to manipulate because they allow fast and easy sequential access to the list in both directions.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In a doubly linked list, one can insert or delete a node in a constant number of operations given only that node's address.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] To do the same in a singly linked list, one must have the *address of the pointer* to that node, which is either the handle for the whole list (in case of the first node) or the link field in the *previous* node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Some algorithms require access in both directions.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] On the other hand, doubly linked lists do not allow tail-sharing and cannot be used as persistent data structures.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A circularly linked list may be a natural option to represent arrays that are naturally circular, e.g. the corners of a polygon, a pool of buffers that are used and released in FIFO ("first in, first out") order, or a set of processes that should be time-shared in round-robin order.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In these applications, a pointer to any node serves as a handle to the whole list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] With a circular list, a pointer to the last node gives easy access also to the first node, by following one link.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Thus, in applications that require access to both ends of the list (e.g., in the implementation of a queue), a circular structure allows one to handle the structure by a single pointer, instead of two.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A circular list can be split into two circular lists, in constant time, by giving the addresses of the last node of each piece.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The operation consists in swapping the contents of the link fields of those two nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Applying the same operation to any two nodes in two distinct lists joins the two list into one.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This property greatly simplifies some algorithms and data structures, such as the quad-edge and face-edge.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The simplest representation for an empty *circular* list (when such a thing makes sense) is a null pointer, indicating that the list has no nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Without this choice, many algorithms have to test for this special case, and handle it separately.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] By contrast, the use of null to denote an empty *linear* list is more natural and often creates fewer special cases.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] For some applications, it can be useful to use singly linked lists that can vary between being circular and being linear, or even circular with a linear initial segment.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Algorithms for searching or otherwise operating on these have to take precautions to avoid accidentally entering an endless loop.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] One well-known method is to have a second pointer walking the list at half or double the speed, and if both pointers meet at the same node, a cycle has been found.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Sentinel node may simplify certain list operations, by ensuring that the next or previous nodes exist for every element, and that even empty lists have at least one node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] One may also use a sentinel node at the end of the list, with an appropriate data field, to eliminate some end-of-list tests.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] For example, when scanning the list looking for a node with a given value *x*, setting the sentinel's data field to *x* makes it unnecessary to test for end-of-list inside the loop.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Another example is the merging two sorted lists: if their sentinels have data fields set to +∞, the choice of the next output node does not need special handling for empty lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] However, sentinel nodes use up extra space (especially in applications that use many short lists), and they may complicate other operations (such as the creation of a new empty list).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] However, if the circular list is used merely to simulate a linear list, one may avoid some of this complexity by adding a single sentinel node to every list, between the last and the first data nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] With this convention, an empty list consists of the sentinel node alone, pointing to itself via the next-node link.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The list handle should then be a pointer to the last data node, before the sentinel, if the list is not empty; or to the sentinel itself, if the list is empty.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The same trick can be used to simplify the handling of a doubly linked linear list, by turning it into a circular doubly linked list with a single sentinel node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] However, in this case, the handle should be a single pointer to the dummy node itself.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] When manipulating linked lists in-place, care must be taken to not use values that have been invalidated in previous assignments.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This makes algorithms for inserting or deleting linked list nodes somewhat subtle.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This section gives pseudocode for adding or removing nodes from singly, doubly, and circularly linked lists in-place.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Throughout, *null* is used to refer to an end-of-list marker or sentinel, which may be implemented in a number of ways.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The node data structure will have two fields.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] There is also a variable, *firstNode* which always points to the first node in the list, or is *null* for an empty list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The following code inserts a node after an existing node in a singly linked list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Inserting a node before an existing one cannot be done directly; instead, one must keep track of the previous node and insert a node after it.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Inserting at the beginning of the list requires a separate function.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Similarly, there are functions for removing the node *after* a given node, and for removing a node from the beginning of the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] To find and remove a particular node, one must again keep track of the previous element.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Notice that `removeBeginning()` sets `list.firstNode` to `null` when removing the last node in the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Since it is not possible to iterate backwards, efficient `insertBefore` or `removeBefore` operations are not possible.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Inserting to a list before a specific node requires traversing the list, which would have a worst case running time of O(n).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Appending one linked list to another can be inefficient unless a reference to the tail is kept as part of the List structure, because it is needed to traverse the entire first list in order to find the tail, and then append the second list to this.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Thus, if two linearly linked lists are each of length n , list appending has asymptotic time complexity of $O(n)$ .
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In the Lisp family of languages, list appending is provided by the `append` procedure.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Many of the special cases of linked list operations can be eliminated by including a dummy element at the front of the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This ensures that there are no special cases for the beginning of the list and renders both `insertBeginning()` and `removeBeginning()` unnecessary, i.e., every element or node is next to another node (even the first node is next to the dummy node).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In this case, the first useful data in the list will be found at `list.**firstNode**.next`.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In a circularly linked list, all nodes are linked in a continuous circle, without using *null.* For lists with a front and a back (such as a queue), one stores a reference to the last node in the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The *next* node after the last node is the first node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Elements can be added to the back of the list and removed from the front in constant time.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Circularly linked lists can be either singly or doubly linked.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Both types of circularly linked lists benefit from the ability to traverse the full list beginning at any given node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This often allows us to avoid storing *firstNode* and *lastNode*, although if the list may be empty, there needs to be a special representation for the empty list, such as a *lastNode* variable which points to some node in the list or is *null* if it is empty; it uses such a *lastNode* here.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This representation significantly simplifies adding and removing nodes with a non-empty list, but empty lists are then a special case.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Notice that the test "**while** node ≠ someNode" must be at the end of the loop.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If the test was moved to the beginning of the loop, the procedure would fail whenever the list had only one node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This function inserts a node "newNode" into a circular linked list after a given node "node".
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If "node" is null, it assumes that the list is empty.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Suppose that "L" is a variable pointing to the last node of a circular linked list (or null if the list is empty).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This function inserts a value "newVal" before a given node "node" in O(1) time.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A new node has been created between "node" and the next node, then puts the value of "node" into that new node, and puts "newVal" in "node".
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Thus, a singly linked circularly linked list with only a *firstNode* variable can both insert to the front and back in O(1) time.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This function removes a non-null node from a list of size greater than 1 in O(1) time.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] It copies data from the next node into the node, and then sets the node's *next* pointer to skip over the next node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Languages that do not support any type of reference can still create links by replacing pointers with array indices.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The approach is to keep an array of records, where each record has integer fields indicating the index of the next (and possibly previous) node in the array.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Not all nodes in the array need be used.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If records are also not supported, parallel arrays can often be used instead.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A linked list can be built by creating an array of these structures, and an integer variable to store the index of the first element.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Links between elements are formed by placing the array index of the next (or previous) cell into the Next or Prev field within a given element.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In the above example, `ListHead` would be set to 2, the location of the first entry in the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Notice that entry 3 and 5 through 7 are not part of the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] These cells are available for any additions to the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] By creating a `ListFree` integer variable, a free list could be created to keep track of what cells are available.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If all entries are in use, the size of the array would have to be increased or some elements would have to be deleted before new entries could be stored in the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This approach has one main disadvantage, however: it creates and manages a private memory space for its nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] For these reasons, this approach is mainly used for languages that do not support dynamic memory allocation.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] These disadvantages are also mitigated if the maximum size of the list is known at the time the array is created.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Many programming languages such as Lisp and Scheme have singly linked lists built in.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In many functional languages, these lists are constructed from nodes, each called a *cons* or *cons cell*.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The cons has two fields: the *car*, a reference to the data for that node, and the *cdr*, a reference to the next node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Although cons cells can be used to build other data structures, this is their primary purpose.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In languages that support abstract data types or templates, linked list ADTs or templates are available for building linked lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In other languages, linked lists are typically built using references together with records.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] When constructing a linked list, one is faced with the choice of whether to store the data of the list directly in the linked list nodes, called *internal storage*, or merely to store a reference to the data, called *external storage*.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Internal storage has the advantage of making access to the data more efficient, requiring less storage overall, having better locality of reference, and simplifying memory management for the list (its data is allocated and deallocated at the same time as the list nodes).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] External storage, on the other hand, has the advantage of being more generic, in that the same data structure and machine code can be used for a linked list no matter what the size of the data is.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] It also makes it easy to place the same data in multiple linked lists.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Although with internal storage the same data can be placed in multiple lists by including multiple *next* references in the node data structure, it would then be necessary to create separate routines to add or delete cells based on each field.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] It is possible to create additional linked lists of elements that use internal storage by using external storage, and having the cells of the additional linked lists store references to the nodes of the linked list containing the data.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In general, if a set of data structures needs to be included in linked lists, external storage is the best approach.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If a set of data structures need to be included in only one linked list, then internal storage is slightly better, unless a generic linked list package using external storage is available.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Likewise, if different sets of data that can be stored in the same data structure are to be included in a single linked list, then internal storage would be fine.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Another approach that can be used with some languages involves having different data structures, but all have the initial fields, including the *next* (and *prev* if double linked list) references in the same location.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] After defining separate structures for each type of data, a generic structure can be defined that contains the minimum amount of data shared by all the other structures and contained at the top (beginning) of the structures.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Then generic routines can be created that use the minimal structure to perform linked list type operations, but separate routines can then handle the specific data.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This approach is often used in message parsing routines, where several types of messages are received, but all start with the same set of fields, usually including a field for message type.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The generic routines are used to add new messages to a queue when they are received, and remove them from the queue in order to process the message.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The message type field is then used to call the correct routine to process the specific type of message.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Notice that when using external storage, an extra step is needed to extract the record from the node and cast it into the proper data type.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This is because both the list of families and the list of members within the family are stored in two linked lists using the same data structure (*node*), and this language does not have parametric types.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] As long as the number of families that a member can belong to is known at compile time, internal storage works fine.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] If, however, a member needed to be included in an arbitrary number of families, with the specific number known only at run time, external storage would be necessary.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Finding a specific element in a linked list, even if it is sorted, normally requires O(*n*) time (linear search).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This is one of the primary disadvantages of linked lists over other data structures.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In addition to the variants discussed above, below are two simple ways to improve search time.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] In an unordered list, one simple heuristic for decreasing average search time is the *move-to-front heuristic*, which simply moves an element to the beginning of the list once it is found.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This scheme, handy for creating simple caches, ensures that the most recently used items are also the quickest to find again.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Another common approach is to "index" a linked list using a more efficient external data structure.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] For example, one can build a red–black tree or hash table whose elements are references to the linked list nodes.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Multiple such indexes can be built on a single list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The disadvantage is that these indexes may need to be updated each time a node is added or removed (or at least, before that index is used again).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A random-access list is a list with support for fast random access to read or modify any element in the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] One possible implementation is a skew binary random-access list using the skew binary number system, which involves a list of trees with special properties; this allows worst-case constant time head/cons operations, and worst-case logarithmic time random access to an element by index.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Random-access lists can be implemented as persistent data structures.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Random-access lists can be viewed as immutable linked lists in that they likewise support the same O(1) head and tail operations.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A simple extension to random-access lists is the min-list, which provides an additional operation that yields the minimum element in the entire list in constant time (without mutation complexities).
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Both stacks and queues are often implemented using linked lists, and simply restrict the type of operations which are supported.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The skip list is a linked list augmented with layers of pointers for quickly jumping over large numbers of elements, and then descending to the next layer.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This process continues down to the bottom layer, which is the actual list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A binary tree can be seen as a type of linked list where the elements are themselves linked lists of the same nature.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] The result is that each node may include a reference to the first node of one or two other linked lists, which, together with their contents, form the subtrees below that node.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] An unrolled linked list is a linked list in which each node contains an array of data values.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] This leads to improved cache performance, since more list elements are contiguous in memory, and reduced memory overhead, because less metadata needs to be stored for each element of the list.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A hash table may use linked lists to store the chains of items that hash to the same position in the hash table.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A heap shares some of the ordering properties of a linked list, but is almost always implemented using an array.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] Instead of references from node to node, the next and previous data indexes are calculated using the current data's index.
[src:skip-list/linked-list] A self-organizing list rearranges its nodes based on some heuristic which reduces search times for data retrieval by keeping commonly accessed nodes at the head of the list.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] In computer science, the **treap** and the **randomized binary search tree** are two closely related forms of binary search tree data structures that maintain a dynamic set of ordered keys and allow binary searches among the keys.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The treap was first described by Raimund Seidel and Cecilia R.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Aragon in 1989; its name is a portmanteau of tree and heap.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] It is a Cartesian tree in which each key is given a (randomly chosen) numeric priority.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] As with any binary search tree, the inorder traversal order of the nodes is the same as the sorted order of the keys.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The structure of the tree is determined by the requirement that it be heap-ordered: that is, the priority number for any non-leaf node must be greater than or equal to the priority of its children.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Thus, as with Cartesian trees more generally, the root node is the maximum-priority node, and its left and right subtrees are formed in the same manner from the subsequences of the sorted order to the left and right of that node.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] An equivalent way of describing the treap is that it could be formed by inserting the nodes highest priority-first into a binary search tree without doing any rebalancing.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Because random binary search trees are known to have logarithmic height with high probability, the same is true for treaps.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] This mirrors the binary search tree argument that quicksort runs in expected $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] If binary search trees are solutions to the dynamic problem version of sorting, then Treaps correspond specifically to dynamic quicksort where priorities guide pivot choices.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Aragon and Seidel also suggest assigning higher priorities to frequently accessed nodes, for instance by a process that, on each access, chooses a random number and replaces the priority of the node with that number if it is higher than the previous priority.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] This modification would cause the tree to lose its random shape; instead, frequently accessed nodes would be more likely to be near the root of the tree, causing searches for them to be faster.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Naor and Nissim describe an application in maintaining authorization certificates in public-key cryptosystems.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] In addition to the single-element insert, delete and lookup operations, several fast "bulk" operations have been defined on treaps: union, intersection and set difference.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] These rely on two helper operations, *split* and *join*.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The union of two treaps *t*1 and *t*2, representing sets A and B is a treap *t* that represents *A* ∪ *B*.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Here, *split* is presumed to return two trees: one holding the keys less than its input key, one holding the greater keys.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The algorithm for intersection is similar, but requires the *join* helper routine.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The complexity of each of union, intersection and difference is *O*(*m* log ⁠*n*/*m*⁠) for treaps of sizes m and n, with *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Moreover, since the recursive calls to union are independent of each other, they can be executed in parallel.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Split and Union call Join but do not deal with the balancing criteria of treaps directly, such an implementation is usually called the "join-based" implementation.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Note that if hash values of keys are used as priorities and structurally equal nodes are merged already at construction, then each merged node will be a unique representation of a set of keys.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Provided that there can only be one simultaneous root node representing a given set of keys, two sets can be tested for equality by pointer comparison, which is constant in time.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] This technique can be used to enhance the merge algorithms to perform fast also when the difference between two sets is small.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] If input sets are equal, the union and intersection functions could break immediately returning one of the input sets as result, while the difference function should return the empty set.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Let d be the size of the symmetric difference.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The modified merge algorithms will then also be bounded by *O*(*d* log ⁠*n*/*d*⁠).
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The numbers of descendants are used by the algorithm to calculate the necessary probabilities for the random choices at each step.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Placing *x* at the root of a subtree may be performed either as in the treap by inserting it at a leaf and then rotating it upwards, or by an alternative algorithm described by Martínez and Roura that splits the subtree into two pieces to be used as the left and right children of the new node.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] That is because the subtrees to be joined are on average at depth Θ(log n); joining two trees of size n and m needs Θ(log(n+m)) random choices on average.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] If the left or right subtree of the node to be deleted is empty, the join operation is trivial; otherwise, the left or right child of the deleted node is selected as the new subtree root with probability proportional to its number of descendants, and the join proceeds recursively.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] However, in any case, the differences between the theoretical model of perfect random choices used to design the algorithm and the capabilities of actual random number generators are vanishingly small.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Although the treap and the randomized binary search tree both have the same random distribution of tree shapes after each update, the history of modifications to the trees performed by these two data structures over a sequence of insertion and deletion operations may be different.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] For instance, in a treap, if the three numbers 1, 2, and 3 are inserted in the order 1, 3, 2, and then the number 2 is deleted, the remaining two nodes will have the same parent-child relationship that they did prior to the insertion of the middle number.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] In a randomized binary search tree, the tree after the deletion is equally likely to be either of the two possible trees on its two nodes, independently of what the tree looked like prior to the insertion of the middle number.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The idea behind an implicit treap is to use the array index as a key, but to not store it explicitly.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Otherwise, an update (insertion/deletion) would result in changes of the keys in $O(n)$ nodes of the tree.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] The key value (**implicit key)** of a node T is the number of nodes less than that node plus one.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Note that such nodes can be present not only in its left subtree but also in left subtrees of its ancestors P, if T is in the right subtree of P.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Therefore we can quickly calculate the implicit key of the current node as we perform an operation by accumulating the sum of all nodes as we descend the tree.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Note that this sum does not change when we visit the left subtree but it will increase by $cnt(T\rightarrow L)+1$ when we visit the right subtree.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] To insert an element at position *pos* we divide the array into two subsections *[0...pos-1]* and *[pos..sz]* by calling the ***split*** function and we get two trees $T1$ and $T2$ .
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Then we merge $T1$ with the new node by calling the ***join*** function.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] Finally we call the join function to merge $T1$ and $T2$ .
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] We find the element to be deleted and perform a join on its children L and R.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] We then replace the element to be deleted with the tree that resulted from the join operation.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] To show that the subtree of a given node needs to be reversed for each node we will create an extra boolean field R and set its value to true.
[src:skip-list/randomized-binary-search-tree] To propagate this change we will swap the children of the node and set R to true for all of them.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] In computer science, a **search data structure** is any data structure that allows the efficient retrieval of specific items from a set of items, such as a specific record from a database.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] The simplest, most general, and least efficient search structure is merely an unordered sequential list of all the items.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] Locating the desired item in such a list, by the linear search method, inevitably requires a number of operations proportional to the number *n* of items, in the worst case as well as in the average case.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] Useful search data structures allow faster retrieval; however, they are limited to queries of some specific kind.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] Moreover, since the cost of building such structures is at least proportional to *n*, they only pay off if several queries are to be performed on the same database (or on a database that changes little between queries).
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] The simplest kind of query is to locate a record that has a specific field (the *key*) equal to a specified value *v*.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] Other common kinds of query are "find the item with smallest (or largest) key value", "find the item with largest key value not exceeding *v*", "find all items with key values between specified bounds *v*min and *v*max".
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] In certain databases the key values may be points in some multi-dimensional space.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] For example, the key may be a geographic position (latitude and longitude) on the Earth.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] In that case, common kinds of queries are "find the record with a key closest to a given point *v*", or "find all items whose key lies at a given distance from *v*", or "find all items within a specified region *R* of the space".
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] A common special case of the latter are simultaneous range queries on two or more simple keys, such as "find all employee records with salary between 50,000 and 100,000 and hired between 1995 and 2007".
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] This table is only an approximate summary; for each data structure there are special situations and variants that may lead to different costs.
[src:skip-list/search-data-structure] Also two or more data structures can be combined to obtain lower costs.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Skip graphs have the full functionality of a balanced tree in a distributed system.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Skip graphs are mostly used in searching peer-to-peer networks.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] As they provide the ability to query by key ordering, they improve over search tools based on the hash table functionality only.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] In contrast to skip lists and other tree data structures, they are very resilient and can tolerate a large fraction of node failures.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] In addition, constructing, inserting, searching, and repairing a skip graph that was disturbed by failing nodes can be done by straightforward algorithms.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] A skip graph is a distributed data structure based on skip lists designed to resemble a balanced search tree.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] They are one of several methods to implement a distributed hash table, which are used to locate resources stored in different locations across a network, given the name (or key) of the resource.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] A major distinction from Chord and Tapestry is that there is no hashing of search keys of resources, which allows related resources to be near each other in the skip graph; this property makes searches for values within a given range feasible.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Another strength of skip graphs is the resilience to node failure in both random and adversarial failure models.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] As with skip lists, nodes are arranged in increasing order in multiple levels; each node in level *i* is contained in level *i*+1 with some probability p (an adjustable parameter).
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Level 0 consists of one doubly linked list containing all of the nodes in the set.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Lists becoming increasingly sparse at higher levels, until the list is composed of just one node.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Where skip graphs differ from skip lists is that each level *i*≥1, will contain multiple lists; membership of a key *x* in a list is defined by the **membership vector** ⁠ $m(x)$ ⁠.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] The membership vector is defined as an infinite random word over a fixed alphabet, each list in the skip graph is identified by a finite word *w* from the same alphabet, if that word is a prefix of ⁠ $m(x)$ ⁠ then node x is a member of the list.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Skip graphs support the basic operations of **search**, **insert** and **delete**.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Skip graphs will also support the more complex **range search** operation.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] The search algorithm for skip graphs is almost identical to the search algorithm for skip lists but it is modified to run in a distributed system.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Searches start at the top level and traverse through the structure.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] At each level, the search traverses the list until the next node contains a greater key.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] When a greater key is found, the search drops to the next level, continuing until the key is found or it is determined that the key is not contained in the set of nodes.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] If the key is not contained in the set of nodes the largest value less than the search key is returned.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] An array containing pointers to the right and left neighbor in the node's doubly linked at level i.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Analysis performed by William Pugh shows that on average, a skip list and by extension a skip graph contains $O\left({\frac {\log n}{\log(1/p)}}\right)$ levels for a fixed value of p.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Given that at most ${\frac {1}{1-p}}$ nodes are searched on average per level, the total expected number of messages sent is $O\left({\frac {\log n}{(1-p)\log(1-p)}}\right)$ and the expected time for the search is $O\left({\frac {\log n}{(1-p)\log(1-p)}}\right)$ .
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Therefore, for a fixed value of p, the search operation is expected to take *O*(log *n*) time using *O*(log *n*) messages.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Insertion is done in two phases and requires that a new node u knows some introducing node v; the introducing node may be any other node currently in the skip graph.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] In the first phase the new node u uses the introducing node v to search for its own key; this search is expected to fail and return the node s with the largest key smaller than u.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] In the second phase u inserts itself in each level until it is the only element in a list at the top level.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Insertion at each level is performed using standard doubly linked list operations; the left neighbor's next pointer is changed to point to the new node and the right neighbor's previous pointer is changed to point to the node.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Similar to the search, the insert operation takes expected *O*(log *n*) messages and *O*(log *n*) time.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] With a fixed value of p; the search operation in phase 1 is expected to take *O*(log *n*) time and messages.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] In phase 2 at each level *L* ≥ 0, u communicates with an average 1/*p* other nodes to locate s', this will require *O*(1/*p*) time and messages leading to *O*(1) time and messages for each step in phase 2.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Nodes may be deleted in parallel at each level in *O*(1) time and *O*(log *n*) messages.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] When a node wishes to leave the graph it must send messages to its immediate neighbors to rearrange their next and previous pointers.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] The skip graph contains an average of *O*(log *n*) levels; at each level *u* must send 2 messages to complete a delete operation on a doubly linked list.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] As operations on each level may be done in parallel the delete operation may be finished using *O*(1) time and expected *O*(log *n*) messages.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] In skip graphs, fault tolerance describes the number of nodes which can be disconnected from the skip graph by failures of other nodes.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Two failure models have been examined; random failures and adversarial failures.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] In the random failure model any node may fail independently from any other node with some probability.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] The adversarial model assumes node failures are planned such that the worst possible failure is achieved at each step, the entire skip graph structure is known and failures are chosen to maximize node disconnection.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] A drawback of skip graphs is that there is no **repair mechanism**; currently the only way to remove and to repair a skip graph is to build a new skip graph with surviving nodes.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Skip graphs are highly resistant to random failures.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] By maintaining information on the state of neighbors and using redundant links to avoid failed neighbors, normal operations can continue even with a large number of node failures.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] While the number of failed nodes is less than $O\left({\frac {1}{\log n}}\right)$ the skip graph can continue to function normally.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Simulations performed by James Aspnes show that a skip graph with 131072 nodes was able tolerate up to 60% of its nodes failing before surviving nodes were isolated.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] While other distributed data structures may be able to achieve higher levels of resiliency they tend to be much more complex.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Adversarial failure is difficult to simulate in a large network as it becomes difficult to find worst case failure patterns.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] Theoretical analysis shows that the resilience depends based on the **vertex expansion ratio** of the graph, defined as follows.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] For a set of nodes A in the graph G, the expansion factor is the number of nodes not in A but adjacent to a node in A divided by the number of nodes in A.
[src:skip-list/skip-graph] If skip graphs have a sufficiently large expansion ratio of $\Omega \left({\frac {1}{\log n}}\right)$ then at most ⁠ $O(f\log n)$ ⁠ nodes may be separated, even if up to f failures are specifically targeted.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] In computer science, a **skip list** (or **skiplist**) is a probabilistic data structure that allows ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ average complexity for search as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ average complexity for insertion within an ordered sequence of n elements.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Thus it can get the best features of a sorted array (for searching) while maintaining a linked list-like structure that allows insertion, which is not possible with a static array.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Fast search is made possible by maintaining a linked hierarchy of subsequences, with each successive subsequence skipping over fewer elements than the previous one *(see the picture below)*.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Searching starts in the sparsest subsequence until two consecutive elements have been found, one smaller and one larger than or equal to the element searched for.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Via the linked hierarchy, these two elements link to elements of the next sparsest subsequence, where searching is continued until finally searching in the full sequence.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] The elements that are skipped over may be chosen probabilistically or deterministically, with the former being more common.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] The bottom layer 1 is an ordinary ordered linked list.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Each higher layer acts as an "express lane" for the lists below, where an element in layer i appears in layer $i+1$ with some fixed probability p (two commonly used values for p are $1/2$ or $1/4$ ).
[src:skip-list/skip-list] On average, each element appears in $1/(1-p)$ lists, and the tallest element (usually a special head element at the front of the skip list) appears in all the lists.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] The skip list contains $\log _{1/p}n\,$ (i.e. logarithm base $1/p$ of n ) lists.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] A search for a target element begins at the head element in the top list, and proceeds horizontally until the current element is greater than or equal to the target.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] If the current element is equal to the target, it has been found.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] If the current element is greater than the target, or the search reaches the end of the linked list, the procedure is repeated after returning to the previous element and dropping down vertically to the next lower list.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] The expected number of steps in each linked list is at most $1/p$ , which can be seen by tracing the search path backwards from the target until reaching an element that appears in the next higher list or reaching the beginning of the current list.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Therefore, the total *expected* cost of a search is ${\tfrac {1}{p}}\log _{1/p}n$ which is ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)\,$ , when p is a constant.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] By choosing different values of p , it is possible to trade search costs against storage costs.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] For example, the value $p=1/e$ minimizes the average search time of skip lists, whereas the value $p=1/2$ simplifies their implementation.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] The elements used for a skip list can contain more than one pointer since they can participate in more than one list.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Insertions and deletions are implemented much like the corresponding linked-list operations, except that "tall" elements must be inserted into or deleted from more than one linked list.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] (Choose the level of the i'th finite node to be 1 plus the number of times it is possible to repeatedly divide i by 2 before it becomes odd.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Also, i=0 for the negative infinity header as there is the usual special case of choosing the highest possible level for negative and/or positive infinite nodes.) However this also allows someone to know where all of the higher-than-level 1 nodes are and delete them.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Like the derandomized version, quasi-randomization is only done when there is some other reason to be running an ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ operation (which visits every node).
[src:skip-list/skip-list] The advantage of this quasi-randomness is that it doesn't give away nearly as much level-structure related information to an adversarial user as the de-randomized one.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] This is desirable because an adversarial user who is able to tell which nodes are not at the lowest level can pessimize performance by simply deleting higher-level nodes.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] (Bethea and Reiter however argue that nonetheless an adversary can use probabilistic and timing methods to force performance degradation.) The search performance is still guaranteed to be logarithmic.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] It would be tempting to make the following "optimization": In the part which says "Next, for each *i*th...", forget about doing a coin-flip for each even-odd pair.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Just flip a coin once to decide whether to promote only the even ones or only the odd ones.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Instead of ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ coin flips, there would only be ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ of them.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Unfortunately, this gives the adversarial user a 50/50 chance of being correct upon guessing that all of the even numbered nodes (among the ones at level 1 or higher) are higher than level one.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] This is despite the property that there is a very low probability of guessing that a particular node is at level *N* for some integer *N*.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] A skip list does not provide the same absolute worst-case performance guarantees as more traditional balanced tree data structures, because it is always possible (though with very low probability) that the coin-flips used to build the skip list will produce a badly balanced structure.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] However, they work well in practice, and the randomized balancing scheme has been argued to be easier to implement than the deterministic balancing schemes used in balanced binary search trees.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Skip lists are also useful in parallel computing, where insertions can be done in different parts of the skip list in parallel without any global rebalancing of the data structure.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Such parallelism can be especially advantageous for resource discovery in an ad-hoc wireless network because a randomized skip list can be made robust to the loss of any single node.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] For every link, also store the width of the link.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] The width is defined as the number of bottom layer links being traversed by each of the higher layer "express lane" links.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Notice that the width of a higher level link is the sum of the component links below it (i.e. the width 10 link spans the links of widths 3, 2 and 5 immediately below it).
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Consequently, the sum of all widths is the same on every level (10 + 1 = 1 + 3 + 2 + 5 = 1 + 2 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 2).
[src:skip-list/skip-list] To index the skip list and find the i'th value, traverse the skip list while counting down the widths of each traversed link.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Descend a level whenever the upcoming width would be too large.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] For example, to find the node in the fifth position (Node 5), traverse a link of width 1 at the top level.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Now four more steps are needed but the next width on this level is ten which is too large, so drop one level.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Since another step of width 2 would be too far, drop down to the bottom level.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Now traverse the final link of width 1 to reach the target running total of 5 (1+3+1).
[src:skip-list/skip-list] Skip lists were first described in 1989 by William Pugh.
[src:skip-list/skip-list] There are also several US patents for using skip lists to implement (lockless) priority queues and concurrent dictionaries.
